In .NET MAUI, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in your `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is paused
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is stopped
            }));
#elif IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(application =>
            {
                // Runs when the app enters background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- The `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` directives ensure platform code only compiles for the target platform.
- Android provides granular hooks: `OnPause` (partially visible) → `OnStop` (fully hidden).
- iOS uses `DidEnterBackground` for the equivalent combined transition.
- Other available events include `OnResume`, `OnDestroy` (Android) and `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate` (iOS).
